  "prompt": "How is the part of the throat behind the nose called? What function does it serve?",
  "response": "The part of the throat behind the nose is called the \"nasopharynx.\" It is the uppermost section of the pharynx (throat) and plays several important functions:\n\n1. Respiratory function:\n- Serves as a passageway for air during breathing\n- Connects the nasal cavity to the rest of the respiratory tract\n\n2. Auditory function:\n- Contains the Eustachian tubes (auditory tubes) that connect the middle ear to the nasopharynx\n- Helps equalize air pressure between the middle ear and the outside environment\n\n3. Immune system support:\n- Houses adenoids (pharyngeal tonsils), which are part of the lymphatic system\n- Helps defend against infections by trapping and fighting pathogens\n\n4. Speech and resonance:\n- Contributes to the acoustic properties of human voice\n- Acts as a resonating chamber during speech production\n\nAnatomically, the nasopharynx is located above the soft palate and behind the nasal cavity. It is lined with mucous membrane and plays a crucial role in breathing, hearing, and immune defense.",
